



How many Spanish speakers live in South America?

The population of South America is about 440 million [pop-south-america]. However, about 210 million of these people are from Brazil, where the main language spoken is Portugese.
Of course, neither of these linguistic regions are absolute, with all countries having smaller populations that don't speak the most common language. To make a conservative estimate, 
I'll treat all non-Brazilians as Spanish speakers, while also including the estimated 8-million Spanish speakers within Brazil [cite this].

This brings us to a total of 238 million South American Spanish speakers.

How many Spanish speakers live in the United States?

About 60 million people in the United States speak Spanish.

How many English speakers live in the United States? 

About 245 million people speak *only* English at home in the United States. Among those who speak Spanish at home (about 41 million), approximately 25 million speak English "very well".
To keep the estimate conservative, I'm not going to count the 15 million or so who speak English "less than very well", according to the census beureau. I'll also be 
leaving off the English-speaking population for those groups that speak neither English nor Spanish in the home.

This brings us to 270 million English speakers in the United States.



Totals

So if we imagined a scenario where absolutely everybody in South America immigrated into the United States,
we would end up with about 298 million Spanish speakers, and 270 million English speakers.


